CATEGORIES:Academic/Educational
DESCRIPTION:\n\n\n \n\n\n\n\nImmigrant policy in the United States is incr
 easingly shaped not only by the law and enforcement\, but by religious rh
 etoric which frames exclusion as moral necessity. The Department of Relig
 ion hosts Dr. Thomas Lecaque for a lecture examining how faith-based symb
 olism and Christian imagery are mobilized to shield aggressive immigratio
 n enforcement\, including the expanding justification and visibility of I
 CE. By situating these developments within broader U.S. religious and pol
 itical histories\, the lecture critically considers how religion can sacr
 alize state power\, normalize fear\, and reshape public understandings of
  belonging\, citizenship\, race\, and human dignity.\n \nThis event will 
 take place on Zoom. Please register here\n\n\nHosted by: College of Human
 ities and Social Sciences (CHSS)\n\nAdditional Information can be found a
 t: https://montclair.campuslabs.com/engage/event/12351953
DTEND:20260325T233000Z
DTSTAMP:20260322T024908Z
DTSTART:20260325T220000Z
LOCATION:Virtual Event
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Faith and Fear: Religion and Anti-Immigrant Discourse in the U.S.
